{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474467"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:21:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:21:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12182"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12182"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.17,0.14,0.49,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104776"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4710"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12182"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87141"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"157"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8265"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44116"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104776"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department having a seizure. This seizure started about 20 minutes ago. His mother says he has been irritable over the last two days and she has noticed some lumps on the sides of his neck and he has been feverish. He is normally in good health and this is his first seizure. On examination, his temperature is 38.5\u00b0C, pulse rate is 140/min, respiratory rate is 30/min, and blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is given two doses of midazolam five minutes apart and one dose of levetiracetam five minutes later. Another five minutes passes and his condition remains unchanged - he continues to seize. though he remains normotensive, and is maintaining his own airway with oxygen saturations of 97% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intubate patient","Administer repeat dose of levetiracetam","Administer sodium valproate","Administer phenytoin","Observe and reassess in 5 minutes"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child is experiencing a prolonged febrile seizure, which at 20 minutes duration is considered status epilepticus. The clinical picture suggests roseola infantum (Human Herpesvirus 6 infection) as the likely cause, given the combination of fever, irritability, lymphadenopathy, and age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the APLS guidelines, the management of status epilepticus in children follows this stepwise approach:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E0-5 minutes: Assess and support ABC, administer high-flow oxygen, check blood glucose\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5 minutes from onset of seizure: Administer first dose of benzodiazepine (midazolam, lorazepam, or diazepam)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5 minutes after first dose of benzodiazepine: Administer second dose of benzodiazepine if seizure continues\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5 minutes after second dose of benzodiazepine: Administer either \u003Cstrong\u003Ephenytoin\u003C/strong\u003E or levetiracetam\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5 minutes after infusion finished: Administer the other of phenytoin or levetiracetam, or consider phenobarbital\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5 minutes after second infusion finished: Consider rapid sequence induction and intubation for general anaesthesia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister phenytoin\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct next step. As the patient has already received two doses of midazolam and one dose of levetiracetam without effect, phenytoin should be administered next according to the APLS algorithm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister repeat dose of levetiracetam\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The guidelines recommend switching to a different anticonvulsant at this stage rather than repeating the same medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister sodium valproate\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended in the APLS guidelines for acute management of status epilepticus in children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubate patient\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature at this stage. The patient is maintaining his airway and oxygenation. Intubation and general anaesthesia are typically considered if seizures persist beyond 60 minutes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObserve and reassess in 5 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially dangerous. Active treatment should continue as the seizure has already lasted 20 minutes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while this seizure likely has a febrile cause, any seizure lasting more than 30 minutes (or two or more seizures without full recovery in between) should be managed as status epilepticus, regardless of the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Status epilepticus management in children follows a stepwise approach: benzodiazepine \u003E repeat benzodiazepine \u003E phenytoin or levetiracetam \u003E phenobarbital or general anaesthesia.","Febrile seizures lasting more than 30 minutes should be managed as status epilepticus.","Roseola infantum is a common cause of febrile seizures in young children."],"references":["Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Seizures: acute management. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Seizures_acute_management/","Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Febrile seizure. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Febrile_seizure/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87141"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12182"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87141"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-04T14:01:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-04T14:01:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4710"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104776"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":